</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Tone mapping can also be used as an effect to produce distinctive images from scenes where the dynamic range may — but need not to — be particularly high. A visual effect characteristic of some local tone mapping operators is the production of bright 'halos' around darker objects, such as that which can be seen in the Cornell Law School photo. No, this is not a visual effect nor it is wanted effect in photogpraphy. These halos are poor example of inadequate HDR-image where the original photos do not contain enough information. Original photos are not shot so that the histogram goes beyond dynamic range of regular photo's light and dark.</p>
